00:03:58.559 --> 00:03:59.639
Sophistication is irrelevant, right?

00:03:59.639 --> 00:04:02.039
Are you providing value is the right question.

00:04:02.039 --> 00:04:05.759
And so how do we deploy to increase value?

00:04:05.759 --> 00:04:07.919
How was I going to do that?

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:11.559
And so there were sort of three principles that I took as my guides.

00:04:11.559 --> 00:04:14.679
And the first one was that I wanted to make my content accessible.

00:04:14.679 --> 00:04:18.440
And what that meant is that people who should have access to the content can get it when

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:21.679
they need it and somewhere that they know where to find it.

00:04:21.679 --> 00:04:23.200
The second thing was reproducible, right?

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:29.119
Can I reliably understand how the content exists, why it is the way it is?

00:04:29.119 --> 00:04:30.480
Can I sort of audit it?

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:31.480
And then secure.

00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:34.640
And that's sort of the inverse of accessible, right?

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:37.559
People who shouldn't have access don't have access.

00:04:37.959 --> 00:04:40.600
That's pretty important.

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:43.200
So the question is, how do I get there?

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:46.559
And this is honestly not a trivial problem, right?

00:04:46.559 --> 00:04:50.320
In particular, in between those important train steps with my data, I have to store

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:52.119
that data somewhere.

00:04:52.119 --> 00:04:56.640
And then in between training and serving the model, I have to store that model somewhere.

00:04:56.640 --> 00:04:59.959
And until recently, this wasn't a solved problem.

00:04:59.959 --> 00:05:03.940
I could put the analysis data in a database if I have one handy, if I have right privileges

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:05.359
to one, that's fine.

00:05:05.359 --> 00:05:09.079
But if I don't or if I don't want to put it in a database for some reason, there kind

00:05:09.079 --> 00:05:11.000
of was no good answer there.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.160
And similarly with modeling, there was kind of no good answer.

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:22.200
So I went back to Star Wars, went back to not working on this, because that was easier.

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:28.399
And of course, Yoda came to my rescue yet again, saying, you know, when hopeless the

00:05:28.399 --> 00:05:31.839
task seems, come out with a sweet new R package.

00:05:31.839 --> 00:05:33.399
Someone will.

00:05:33.399 --> 00:05:35.880
It's inevitable.

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:36.880
And of course, that was true.

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:40.600
The pins package is a new package by Javier Larrache, he's here at RStudio.

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:43.679
And this is a super cool package, I'm super excited about it.

00:05:43.679 --> 00:05:49.000
Basically, what it lets you do is take something, an R object, put it somewhere else, and then

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:50.279
get it back when you want it.

00:05:50.279 --> 00:05:52.559
This is sort of the essence of the pins package.

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:56.160
But let's go into a little more detail about exactly how it works.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:59.480
So I'm going to start off with my R, my RStudio session, and I have an object I want to save.

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:00.480
You can think like a data frame.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:01.480
It could also be a model.

00:06:01.559 --> 00:06:05.000
It could be any sort of S3 compliant object.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.480
And I have a board also, and my board is where I'm going to save it.

00:06:08.480 --> 00:06:12.480
Pins currently supports a bunch of different boards, so RStudio Connect, Kaggle, GitHub,

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:17.079
Azure, Google Cloud Platform, S3, or a website, Javier is constantly adding new boards I will

00:06:17.079 --> 00:06:18.079
also add.

00:06:18.079 --> 00:06:20.799
So if you want something that isn't here, put it on GitHub and he'll probably have it

00:06:20.799 --> 00:06:21.799
done before the end of conf.

00:06:21.799 --> 00:06:23.640
It's kind of incredible.

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:27.079
But that aside, it supports a lot of different places that you can put your data, great.

00:06:27.079 --> 00:06:29.279
So it's really easy to use as well.

00:06:29.279 --> 00:06:34.440
You put your data onto the board with the pins pin command, and get it back with the

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:36.160
pins pin get command.

