00:08:25.799 --> 00:08:29.000
So the question is sort of, you know, what are good things to pin and what are bad things?

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.719
Obviously you don't want to store every single R object you've ever used in a pin.

00:08:34.719 --> 00:08:41.440
So again, wisdom from Yoda, just before Luke goes off to fight Vader at Cloud City, and

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:42.440
it's a disaster.

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:43.440
Anyway.

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:46.960
Before that, though, Yoda gives him some very sage advice.

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:50.400
Best considered a caching mechanism, pins are.

00:08:50.400 --> 00:08:54.559
And what this means, A, it's kind of, you know, this movie came out in 1980, and this

00:08:54.559 --> 00:08:58.320
package came out in 2020, so this is very impressive to begin with.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:00.440
But even more impressive that he's right.

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:05.940
And so, you know, you generally don't want to save your data of record in a pin, right?

00:09:05.940 --> 00:09:07.520
It's not a database.

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:11.580
It doesn't have all the, like, bells and whistles of a database, being able to audit.

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:13.979
It's not a database replacement.

00:09:13.979 --> 00:09:17.619
What pins are great for is they're great for something that you could compute at the time

00:09:17.619 --> 00:09:21.419
or you could get at the time, but it's easier to store it somewhere, right?

00:09:21.419 --> 00:09:25.179
You'd rather cache it rather than recreating it on demand.

00:09:25.179 --> 00:09:28.580
And so there are three attributes that good candidates for a pin have, and that is that

00:09:28.580 --> 00:09:31.260
they're relatively small, say, like, a gigabyte.

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:34.820
There's no hard rule, but a gigabyte is a good rule of thumb.

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:39.059
They're reused, that you actually want this thing over and over and over again in different

00:09:39.059 --> 00:09:42.260
pieces of your content, and that they're current, right?

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:43.299
You want the tip of the pin.

00:09:43.299 --> 00:09:44.659
You only care about the newest version.

00:09:44.659 --> 00:09:48.619
If you care about archival versions, a pin is not a great choice, but if you care about

00:09:48.619 --> 00:09:50.780
just the newest one, that's really good.

00:09:50.780 --> 00:09:53.099
And again, you know, pins are for things you can recreate.

00:09:53.099 --> 00:09:56.219
You know, it's not for your data of record.

00:09:56.219 --> 00:09:57.219
That's not a great choice.

00:09:57.219 --> 00:09:59.940
I mean, if you do it, whatever, I'm not going to stop you.

