my testing and training set, and the recipe that I'm using from the recipes package to

00:12:41.299 --> 00:12:43.299
actually make my training data.

00:12:43.299 --> 00:12:46.380
And then I'm pinning that here onto RStudio Connect.

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:47.460
And this is super useful, right?

00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:51.179
Now I have a really good way to know what I've done.

00:12:51.179 --> 00:12:56.340
And then last, my Plumber API that's serving those predictions, I've got my model.

00:12:56.340 --> 00:12:58.299
I'm reading it in here.

00:12:58.299 --> 00:13:05.020
And then all this code, basically, is just sort of interpreting the input from the API

00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:07.020
and making sure it's ready to be fed into the model.

00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:10.500
And then down here, right, I'm running that predict command on that model that's from

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:11.500
the pin.

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:13.780
And this is purring away on RStudio Connect.

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:18.659
And so I can come here to the Swagger interface and get back, you know, these are the predictions

00:13:18.659 --> 00:13:19.659
for station 75.

00:13:19.659 --> 00:13:21.900
I don't know what station that is.

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:26.619
But that's why I have the other one, the other pin with the station names.

00:13:26.619 --> 00:13:31.820
So that's how pins sort of fit into this app.

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:33.219
So now I've got a solution for this, right?

00:13:33.219 --> 00:13:36.219
For my analysis data, I can do it in a database or in a pin.

00:13:36.219 --> 00:13:38.940
For my model, I can do it in a pin.

00:13:38.940 --> 00:13:41.500
One thing I do want to say is, like, these are just slots.

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:43.299
And you can put whatever you want into these slots.

00:13:43.299 --> 00:13:48.619
So for example, if you're using some model in Python or some import method in Python,

00:13:48.619 --> 00:13:51.460
you can totally do that and use reticulate to go back and forth between R and Python

00:13:51.460 --> 00:13:53.260
super easily.

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:57.179
If what you're serving isn't a model, if it's, you know, plots or just some kind of

00:13:57.179 --> 00:14:00.900
counting, right, the same principle totally works.

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:04.419
And when you're sharing, right, if what you've got is an R Markdown document that you want

00:14:04.419 --> 00:14:09.099
to render and email out or something like that, again, think of these as slots.

00:14:09.099 --> 00:14:12.739
You know, my version happened to be R Markdown, R Markdown Plumber Shiny app, but yours can

00:14:12.739 --> 00:14:14.659
be whatever you want.

00:14:14.659 --> 00:14:15.780
Okay.

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:21.260
So pins has really helped me a lot make this content more accessible, more reproducible.

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:23.739
But I haven't really addressed security at all.

00:14:23.739 --> 00:14:26.859
And that's a really important piece here.

00:14:26.859 --> 00:14:28.260
The security of my app.

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:30.859
And so, of course, I went back to Yoda.

00:14:30.859 --> 00:14:35.500
And in Return of the Jedi, as Yoda is dying, fading away after 800 years of training Jedi

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:41.739
knights, witnessing the downfall of anyway, okay, sorry, I really like Star Wars.

00:14:41.739 --> 00:14:45.859
He gives this one final piece of advice to Luke, and he says, deploy to the right server

00:14:46.140 --> 00:14:51.739
and secure your data will be, which, you know, I think is very prescient of him.

00:14:51.739 --> 00:14:56.219
And so you can do this in an open source way if that's what you're more comfortable doing.

00:14:56.219 --> 00:15:00.700
For this important training step, put it on a server, any server that has R works.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:03.739
You can use a cron job if you want to schedule it.

00:15:03.739 --> 00:15:07.099
For your analysis data in your model, if you have a database for the database stuff or

00:15:07.099 --> 00:15:09.960
a pins board, I showed there are a whole bunch of options, right?

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:13.640
For serving the model, any server with R, again, can work.

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:17.960
You do have some things you have to be delicate with here around how auth works, so you can

00:15:17.960 --> 00:15:22.440
do that with networking rules, you can put a proxy in front of it, you can route it through

00:15:22.440 --> 00:15:24.320
a Lambda gateway to take care of API keys.

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:29.479
You have lots of options, but you're going to want to do something to secure this API.

00:15:29.479 --> 00:15:30.640
And then for sharing, you have a lot of options.

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:34.880
If it's an R markdown document, either a website or a rendered document, Netlify is a great

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:35.880
choice.

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:40.039
Shiny server open source is available to you, and shinyapps.io is also an option, which

00:15:40.039 --> 00:15:43.080
is not open source, but is relatively affordable.

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:46.960
So that can be a really good option here if you're doing a private thing or something

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:49.640
that's for your own use.

00:15:49.640 --> 00:15:53.280
Of course, we see a lot of organizations that sort of struggle with pieces of this, either

00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:57.960
they don't want to manage this many sort of separate pieces, their IT organizations don't

00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:01.239
want to manage stuff in R. We see that a lot.

00:16:01.239 --> 00:16:02.239
That's totally fine.

00:16:02.239 --> 00:16:06.440
And so, of course, sort of easy mode here is our professional product, RStudio Connect,

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:09.159
and that takes care of a lot of these pieces for you, right?

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:13.799
It can deal with the API keys, it can deal with scheduling the R markdown documents,

00:16:13.799 --> 00:16:17.200
it can deal with securing the plumber APIs, it can deal with, you know, accessibility

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:20.840
controls and that kind of stuff, and you can put pins on RStudio Connect.

00:16:20.840 --> 00:16:26.840
So this can be a really useful way to do all of this.

00:16:26.840 --> 00:16:29.679
So big takeaways.

00:16:29.679 --> 00:16:35.559
When you are thinking about deploying content, the top three things to really optimize for

00:16:35.559 --> 00:16:40.039
are accessibility, reproducibility, and security, right?

00:16:40.039 --> 00:16:44.679
If you're hitting these three keys, you're probably increasing value with what you're

00:16:44.679 --> 00:16:48.200
doing as opposed to just adding sophistication.

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:53.679
While you're doing that, R markdown, Shiny, Plumber, and Pins are good friends of yours.

00:16:53.679 --> 00:16:59.679
And of course, may the force be with you.

00:16:59.679 --> 00:17:13.560
All right, so I failed to mention at the top of things here, but if you have questions,

00:17:13.560 --> 00:17:16.839
we're going to continue using Slido as we did in the keynote.

00:17:16.839 --> 00:17:22.719
So we're in Grand Ballroom B, so if you have a question, go to the same Slido page, select

00:17:22.719 --> 00:17:26.520
Grand Ballroom B, and you can enter your questions there or vote on questions that are already

00:17:26.520 --> 00:17:27.520
asked there.

00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:32.079
So I'm going to ask Alex some questions here since we have a couple minutes.

00:17:32.079 --> 00:17:36.160
Maybe this was covered in the last half of your presentation, but do you want to readdress

00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:40.959
how Pins is different from a well-organized shared file system with correct ACLs?

00:17:40.959 --> 00:17:44.439
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:17:44.439 --> 00:17:46.800
To be honest, under the hood, it's not that different, right?

00:17:46.800 --> 00:17:50.160
You have the same kind of control and access controls.

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:52.719
The main difference is that it's a very R-centric answer.

00:17:52.719 --> 00:17:56.959
And so you can, from within R, address those objects without having to go through the hassle

00:17:56.959 --> 00:18:01.319
of figuring out how your shared file system works, finding things, and that sort of thing.

00:18:01.319 --> 00:18:04.119
So from an IT perspective, maybe not that different.

00:18:04.119 --> 00:18:07.479
But from the perspective of an R developer, it's a very different sort of development

00:18:07.479 --> 00:18:08.479
experience.

00:18:08.479 --> 00:18:09.479
It's much more straightforward.

00:18:09.479 --> 00:18:10.479
Yeah.

00:18:10.479 --> 00:18:14.839
This next one, we get a lot, so I'm happy to ask it here.

00:18:14.839 --> 00:18:20.280
What's the benefit of using a Plumber API for saving the object to S3 and then calling

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:21.280
it with a Shiny app?

00:18:21.280 --> 00:18:22.280
Oh, that's a great question.

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:25.040
I love that question.

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:26.400
There are a couple benefits.

00:18:26.839 --> 00:18:32.040
The biggest benefit to me, and this happens in several different ways, is that it decouples

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:37.400
the logic of serving the model from the logic of displaying whatever you're displaying or

00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:38.520
doing something else with it.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:40.239
So you decouple those things.

00:18:40.239 --> 00:18:41.239
And that makes your life easier.

00:18:41.239 --> 00:18:42.560
It makes your life easier in a couple ways.

00:18:42.560 --> 00:18:45.020
One of them is purely from a code perspective.

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:48.520
It makes it easier to write the code because you write your Plumber API to serve the model,

00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:51.540
you write your Shiny app or whatever it is to consume the model, and you get to sort

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:54.119
of separate those concerns, which is really nice.

00:18:54.119 --> 00:18:58.040
The other piece from a performance perspective, you can test those two things independently.

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:01.599
You can test the Plumber API with, say, the load test package, which I think some people

00:19:01.599 --> 00:19:03.839
might be talking about next.

00:19:03.839 --> 00:19:05.359
And then you can test the Shiny app separately.

00:19:05.359 --> 00:19:11.880
You can decouple both the coding and the performance issues between the API and the app, which is

00:19:11.880 --> 00:19:12.880
great.

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:13.880
Excellent.

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:14.880
Okay.

00:19:14.880 --> 00:19:21.400
Next, is there a limit to the amount of data you should be using with pins?

00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:22.699
It depends on which board you're using.

00:19:22.699 --> 00:19:25.859
Some of those boards do have limits to how much you can save.

00:19:25.859 --> 00:19:30.619
You know, my suggestion would be that if you're saving more than a gigabyte's worth of data,

00:19:30.619 --> 00:19:34.540
there's probably a better solution for what you're doing.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:38.380
And that's totally a rule of thumb, not a real thing.

00:19:38.380 --> 00:19:43.219
But just in general, if you're finding yourself doing more than that, you're probably saving

00:19:43.219 --> 00:19:46.459
an object that's bigger than pins really is designed for.

00:19:46.459 --> 00:19:50.500
One thing that can be helpful is if you're saving model objects, often the model objects

00:19:50.500 --> 00:19:53.619
package up a lot of stuff with it that you don't necessarily want, like the training

00:19:53.619 --> 00:19:54.619
data.

00:19:54.619 --> 00:19:57.979
And that could make your model really big and sort of inflate the size.

00:19:57.979 --> 00:20:04.140
There is a package called butcher, like, you know, a person who makes meat cuts, that you

00:20:04.140 --> 00:20:07.579
can use to sort of chop out some of the stuff in your model object you don't want and just

00:20:07.579 --> 00:20:08.979
save, like, actually the model.

00:20:08.979 --> 00:20:13.780
So if you're saving models, that can be a useful thing to do.

00:20:13.780 --> 00:20:14.780
One more here.

00:20:14.780 --> 00:20:15.780
I like this one as well.

00:20:15.780 --> 00:20:21.140
What's the reason your import and model training code is in R Markdown files instead of plain

00:20:21.140 --> 00:20:22.140
R scripts?

00:20:22.140 --> 00:20:23.140
Yes, that's a great question.

00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:26.540
I love it when things I put in the presentation and took out because I didn't have time come

00:20:26.540 --> 00:20:28.020
back in questions.

00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:31.900
Yeah, so I really love R Markdown for two main reasons.

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:37.060
One is that it encourages literate programming that is interspersing code and prose, right?

00:20:37.060 --> 00:20:38.780
Because you have just, like, a place to write prose.

00:20:38.780 --> 00:20:42.219
It doesn't even have to be comments, you just write it, and it's great.

00:20:42.219 --> 00:20:43.939
The other reason is that you have a record of what you did.

00:20:43.939 --> 00:20:48.099
So when you come back later and something has gone awry with your model, you have output

00:20:48.099 --> 00:20:52.459
there with the code of what actually happened, unlike if it's just an R script and then whatever

00:20:52.459 --> 00:20:55.619
happened was totally ephemeral, and it's gone forever.

00:20:55.619 --> 00:20:59.979
Well, everyone, please join me in thanking Alex again.

00:20:59.979 --> 00:21:00.979
Thanks, everybody.

00:21:00.979 --> 00:21:00.979


